+ modules from cpan

	none currently

INSTALATION
-----------

1.- Configure:

    $ ./configure <arguments>

    Accepts standard GNU configure arguments, run ./configure --help
    for a list

    Apache is autodetected

    Suggested argument: --localstatedir=/var/ , to have variable data
    installed in /var/lib/, instead of the default $prefix/var/lib/

2.- Instalation, as root:

    $ make install

3.- To make ebox run on startup:

    cp tools/ebox /etc/init.d
    ln -s /etc/init.d/ebox /etc/rc2.d/S99ebox

4.- Give write permission to the ebox user (set in $sysconfdir/ebox/ebox.conf)
    in the localstatedir directory: $prefix/var/ebox or /var/lib/ebox if the
    --localstatedir=/var parameter was used, and create directories log and
    tmp inside:

    mkdir /var/lib/ebox/tmp
    mkdir /var/lib/ebox/log
    chown -R ebox.ebox /var/lib/ebox

5.- Allow the apache user to run some root commands via sudo, include
    the output of the ebox-sudoers command in your sudoers file. If the ebox
    user is the only one that needs to use sudo you can just overwrite the
    old file with the output of ebox-sudoers:

    ebox-sudoers > /etc/sudoers

6.- Copy conf/.gconf.path to the $HOME directory of the ebox user and:
	
	mkdir $HOME/gconf
	chown ebox.ebox $HOME/gconf

7.- Remove the link to /etc/init.d/apache from /etc/rc2.d/, the ebox script
     will handle apache starts/stops.

8.- Start ebox:
	
	/etc/init.d/ebox start

RUNNING
-------

The url for the administration interface is (the default apache is 443):

https://<ip address>

The default password is 'ebox'. It may be changed in the general configuration
page.

eBox and apache logs are located in $localstatedir/ebox/log/ 
